{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eaaf416a-38ad-488a-a888-ed25ea4d1e1b","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your project.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, that's typically `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- After saving, open the **Command Palette** → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected, then start a Copilot agent-mode chat to use your tools.\n\nIf you need environment variables, add an `\"env\"` object alongside `\"command\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06faed3f-05d0-4f2a-bedd-f75e4bfe5609","outputTokens":271,"requestId":"3841:2EF340:70CC795:7924E6D:6A03CFDC"},"id":"f054e207-8646-4d8c-8f9e-a8fc2a731d6b","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:12:04.298Z","parentId":"50151b3d-58ae-401d-ae28-e703bfd23b9f"}
